        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&REPLY_ID=70565&TOPIC_ID=8751&FORUM_ID=1&CAT_ID=1&Forum_Title=General+Discussions&Topic_Title=Ask+yourself%28about+petition%29&M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>


        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2">I'm not going to flame anyone, but you guys need to calm down.  Whether if the last petition actually did something, or if VI just decided on a whim to get casters fixed so they'll buy SoL, we have no business sending out petitions just because we think some area of our class might be improved.  Petitions are a last resort - when individual effort fails and EVERYBODY agrees that there's something wrong with the class.  It can't be something sent regularly or it WILL loose its power, if it ever had any.</P><P>There are plenty of things to complain about regarding the necro class, but they are pet peeves(pun? :)) compared to the resist problem EVERY raiding necro was having.  That's why the previous petition HAD to be sent - because the class was dying.  The class is no longer dying now - necros I've talked to online are mostly content about their class except, of course, for a list of minor grievances which EVERY class have.</P><P>Now I'll be the first to say that I don't agree with people who are always looking on the bright side.  Ideally, everybody supported the last petition, but that isn't the case if memory serves me right.  There were several necros, even during that time, who scoffed at the petition and who were perfectly content to stay mana batteries, claiming that everybody should just shut up and accept the necro's role over 50.  There will always be people like that - who like the status quo and are either afraid of or simply dislike change.  But they're not always wrong.  Because there is a time in which the fires of indignity and revolution will burn too hot that it gets out of control, and in the end change becomes change's bane as mob mentality drives people to the extremes - and whatever noble ideal they had in the beginning is forgotten in the wake of destruction and revolution. </P><P>The key here is balance and restraint.  Necromancers have many grievances, but not so many that we can't wait and see what VI pulls out of their sleeves first, and not so many that we can't wait till their programmers finish patching Luclin.  This is NOT a good time to get VI to do something for us - they simply won't care till Luclin is up and working AS INTENDED. </P><P>Furthermore, as much as I support the proposition that pets have a hp increase, I must say that I am in great doubt that it will help us as much as you all think.  However, if you guys *truly* believe that pets need an upgrade, be tactful.  Don't start a necro petition and seem to other classes like we're whiners that just won't stop - tag onto the magician revolution instead.  The mages ARE a dying breed, and they need help, especially now that Beastlords are in.  If anything, a grievance with pets should be issued by THEM to have the best effect.  With them is where I think the pet petition should start, if there ever is one.  The power of a petition backed by the majority of the mage community, and supported by necromancers and possibly beastlords, has probably the best chance of getting this off.</P><P>Let us be the necromancers we play - and be cunning and tactful, and avoid direct petitions that can easily become a dime a dozen if overly used.</P><P><BR>Etadanik the Redeemed<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
